WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:11.950 --> 00:00:14.060
&gt;&gt; Monica Mohindra:
Good morning.

00:00:14.060 --> 00:00:17.530
Welcome to the Library and
the Veterans History Project.

00:00:17.530 --> 00:00:18.830
We're so glad you're here.

00:00:18.830 --> 00:00:20.130
Can everyone hear me?

00:00:20.130 --> 00:00:24.240
I have a cold, so, yeah, great.

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:29.850
I'm so, so just honored
and pleased to be here

00:00:29.850 --> 00:00:34.340
in recognition of Veteran's Day
with colleagues and friends,

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:38.660
our amazing panelists all day
for this all-day symposium.

00:00:38.660 --> 00:00:41.950
The Veteran's History
Project, as you probably know,

00:00:41.950 --> 00:00:46.690
was started in October of 2000
through unanimous legislation

00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:51.400
of Congress and passed into
law by then President Clinton.

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:56.180
And we have over 108,000
individual stories

00:00:56.180 --> 00:01:00.950
of first-person veteran's
experience from World War I

00:01:00.950 --> 00:01:04.360
through the recent
conflicts, and those come to us

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:08.260
through voluntary donation
from the people who create them

00:01:08.260 --> 00:01:10.750
from all over the country.

00:01:10.750 --> 00:01:15.200
Some of them we create ourselves
with our staff and colleagues,

00:01:15.200 --> 00:01:21.650
and the vast majority,
though, come from donation.

00:01:21.650 --> 00:01:25.500
The Veteran's History Project
considers a first-person

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:29.150
narrative to be anything
that speaks

00:01:29.150 --> 00:01:33.680
to that first-person experience,
whether it is an oral history,

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:37.950
our specifications are 30
minutes or longer of audio

00:01:37.950 --> 00:01:39.750
or video oral history.

00:01:39.750 --> 00:01:43.330
But also, items of personal
reflection that tell

00:01:43.330 --> 00:01:45.820
that narrative arc,
so collections of ten

00:01:45.820 --> 00:01:49.130
or more photographs,
letters, documents,

00:01:49.130 --> 00:01:53.180
or 20 or more pages
of journal or memoir.

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:55.960
And that gets us to today and
one of the reasons that we're

00:01:55.960 --> 00:02:01.090
so excited to kick off this
symposium, The Road Back,

00:02:01.090 --> 00:02:05.340
looking at poetry and
literature, participating in it,

00:02:05.340 --> 00:02:08.510
creating it, discussing
it, to cope with

00:02:08.510 --> 00:02:12.260
and express the veterans'
experience.

00:02:12.260 --> 00:02:16.760
I'm really excited to
introduce you to our panelists,

00:02:16.760 --> 00:02:18.880
and I'll do that
in just a second.

00:02:18.880 --> 00:02:24.310
But I also wanted to
acknowledge our panelists

00:02:24.310 --> 00:02:27.670
from the second panel who
will be with us this afternoon

00:02:27.670 --> 00:02:30.550
and invite you to
stay, grab some lunch

00:02:30.550 --> 00:02:33.180
and come back and
see that panel.

00:02:33.180 --> 00:02:37.640
And we also have a film this
afternoon in the Pickford.

00:02:37.640 --> 00:02:39.670
Just so you know,
that's across the street

00:02:39.670 --> 00:02:41.440
in the Madison Building.

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:43.160
And while you're here,
you might as well check

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:46.040
out the World War I
exhibit, which is part

00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:48.580
of the reason we're
all gathering today.

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:52.650
So to begin, I'd like to
share a little bit about each

00:02:52.650 --> 00:02:55.640
of the panelists who are going
to be speaking with us today

00:02:55.640 --> 00:03:00.420
and a little bit about
their organizations.

00:03:00.420 --> 00:03:03.340
Immediately to my left
is Lovella Calica.

00:03:03.340 --> 00:03:05.230
She is a writer,
and I'm reading this

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:07.110
because I want to get it right.

00:03:07.110 --> 00:03:10.060
A writer, photographer
and multimedia artist.

00:03:10.060 --> 00:03:13.620
She is the founder and
director of Warrior Writers,

00:03:13.620 --> 00:03:14.920
a creative community

00:03:14.920 --> 00:03:17.820
for veterans articulating
their experiences.

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:20.760
She has edited four
anthologies of veterans' writing

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:24.130
and artwork, has received
three art and change grants

00:03:24.130 --> 00:03:26.630
from the Leeway Foundation
and was honored

00:03:26.630 --> 00:03:29.590
with the Transformation
Award in 2009.

00:03:29.590 --> 00:03:33.060
A self-published author of
two chat books of her poetry,

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:36.030
she is currently at
work on her next book.

00:03:36.030 --> 00:03:37.490
Lovella is a cofounder

00:03:37.490 --> 00:03:43.630
of the Pilipino-American artist
collective, Tatlo Mestizas

00:03:43.630 --> 00:03:44.980
and served on the board

00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:47.890
of Culture Trust
Greater Philadelphia.

00:03:47.890 --> 00:03:51.030
Having worked closely with
primarily post-9/11 veterans

00:03:51.030 --> 00:03:55.160
for 14 years, she has trained
staff of arts organizations

00:03:55.160 --> 00:03:58.430
and universities around the
country on how to better work

00:03:58.430 --> 00:04:00.480
with and understand veterans.

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:02.720
She is also part of the
Caregiver Program of the VA.

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:06.510
A little about Warrior Writers.

00:04:06.510 --> 00:04:10.250
It's a national nonprofit based
in Philadelphia whose mission is

00:04:10.250 --> 00:04:11.550
to create a culture

00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:13.590
that articulates
veterans' experiences,

00:04:13.590 --> 00:04:16.640
builds a collaborative community
for artistic expression

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:18.830
and bears witness to
war and the full range

00:04:18.830 --> 00:04:21.160
of military experiences.

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:24.750
They employ writing, painting,
photography and a host

00:04:24.750 --> 00:04:28.600
of other mediums to reflect
on those personal experiences

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:30.850
and express them creatively.

00:04:30.850 --> 00:04:34.460
Just to her left is
Mohammed Sheriff.

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:36.040
