00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:37.820
&gt;&gt; Mohamed Sheriff: Yes.

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:39.120
&gt;&gt; Monica Mohindra:
Moe is a literature

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:40.850
and arts education
division coordinator

00:04:40.850 --> 00:04:43.480
at the National Endowment
for the Arts.

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:46.590
Before taking this position,
he managed the translation

00:04:46.590 --> 00:04:49.900
and creative writing
fellowship programs for the NEA.

00:04:49.900 --> 00:04:52.280
Prior to the NEA,
he spent four years

00:04:52.280 --> 00:04:55.080
in the United States Marine
Corps and served in Korea,

00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:58.780
Kuwait, Japan, Marshall
Islands and Iraq.

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:01.810
He received his MFA and
arts graduate certificate

00:05:01.810 --> 00:05:04.300
from American University.

00:05:04.300 --> 00:05:06.010
As you may know, the
National Endowment

00:05:06.010 --> 00:05:09.560
for the Arts was established
by Congress in 1965.

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:12.760
It is an independent
federal agency whose funding

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:15.970
and support gives Americans
the opportunity to participate

00:05:15.970 --> 00:05:19.350
in the arts, exercise
their imaginations

00:05:19.350 --> 00:05:21.910
and develop their
creative capacities.

00:05:21.910 --> 00:05:24.980
Through partnerships with state
arch agencies, local leaders,

00:05:24.980 --> 00:05:29.210
other federal agencies and
the philanthropic sector,

00:05:29.210 --> 00:05:32.320
the NEA supports arts,
learning, affirms

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:35.960
and celebrates America's rich
and diverse cultural heritage

00:05:35.960 --> 00:05:38.840
and extends its work to
promote equal access to the arts

00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:40.980
in every community
across America.

00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:45.310
I love our collection of names.

00:05:45.310 --> 00:05:49.270
Stefanie Takacs is
the executive director

00:05:49.270 --> 00:05:51.290
of the Touchstone
Discussion Project

00:05:51.290 --> 00:05:53.370
where she leads organizational
management

00:05:53.370 --> 00:05:56.380
and oversees educational
curriculum and development,

00:05:56.380 --> 00:05:58.910
teacher training and coaching.

00:05:58.910 --> 00:06:01.290
She codesigned with
Howard Zeiderman,

00:06:01.290 --> 00:06:04.270
Touchstone's cofounder,
completing The Odyssey,

00:06:04.270 --> 00:06:08.680
a Journey Home, an NEH, National
Endowment for the Humanities,

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:13.330
funded program for veterans,

00:06:13.330 --> 00:06:16.140
among other numerous
Touchstone Discussion Programs

00:06:16.140 --> 00:06:19.540
and several textbooks she
developed or codeveloped.

00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:22.230
She is also the author
of five books

00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:26.830
on first peoples published
by Scholastic Press.

00:06:26.830 --> 00:06:30.400
Miss Takacs earned a BA from
Saint Johns College in Annapolis

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:32.220
and an MS in educational
psychology

00:06:32.220 --> 00:06:34.390
from Fordham University.

00:06:34.390 --> 00:06:37.090
As part of her commitment to
ensuring all people have access

00:06:37.090 --> 00:06:39.220
to Touchstone's educational
programs,

00:06:39.220 --> 00:06:42.930
she runs two weekly
discussion groups as a volunteer

00:06:42.930 --> 00:06:47.340
within the Maryland Correctional
Institute for women.

00:06:47.340 --> 00:06:50.300
The Touchstone Discussion
Project is an educational

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:53.420
nonprofit dedicated to
building critical thinkers

00:06:53.420 --> 00:06:54.720
and collaborative leaders

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:56.930
through inclusive
dialog and community.

00:06:56.930 --> 00:07:00.250
Since 1984, their
programs have engaged more

00:07:00.250 --> 00:07:04.320
than five million people from
school children to [inaudible],

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:07.000
from the most vulnerable
and at-risk populations

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:09.820
to executives and
political leaders.

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:12.600
Rooted in collaborative
learning and leading,

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:15.910
they use a train the leader
approach and replicable programs

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:19.470
to partner with teachers,
leaders, community builders

00:07:19.470 --> 00:07:22.540
and volunteers running
Touchstone discussion groups

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:25.900
in 47 countries and
in six languages.

00:07:25.900 --> 00:07:28.180
So you see, it's quite a panel.

00:07:28.180 --> 00:07:34.580
VHP, the Veterans History
Project, is a program

00:07:34.580 --> 00:07:37.460
of the American Folklife Center
here at the Library of Congress.

00:07:37.460 --> 00:07:40.020
And it has been known
since the beginning

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:42.480
when it was called the
Veterans Oral History Project

00:07:42.480 --> 00:07:46.360
as primarily an effort
of oral history.

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:50.130
However, as I mentioned
earlier, we also seek

00:07:50.130 --> 00:07:53.140
to capture the personal
narrative of veterans

00:07:53.140 --> 00:07:59.160
and their experience and notice
the influence and the emphasis

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:01.470
on personal narrative
as expressed

00:08:01.470 --> 00:08:06.390
through the way they want to do
that themselves through letters,

00:08:06.390 --> 00:08:08.860
journal, diaries
and creative works.

00:08:08.860 --> 00:08:11.180
Those creative works
are two-dimensional.

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:12.750
We are not looking
for sculptures

00:08:12.750 --> 00:08:14.720
of spent ammunition, thank you.

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:19.460
But we are looking for poems and
other ways of self-expression

00:08:19.460 --> 00:08:22.580
and that two-dimensional
capacity poetry.

00:08:22.580 --> 00:08:25.040
And I'm going to
take this with me

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:27.420
and disappear behind the podium,

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:33.780
because I found this
amazing collection

00:08:33.780 --> 00:08:37.050
that I think really
illustrates a lot

00:08:37.050 --> 00:08:39.560
of what we're talking
about here today.

00:08:39.560 --> 00:08:43.840
This is Joseph Rosenblum, and
you can see one of the 80 pages

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:45.650
of his journal from World War I.

00:08:45.650 --> 00:08:49.730
Mr. Rosenblum was born
in Romania, in Romania,

00:08:49.730 --> 00:08:54.370
and he was drafted into the
US Army in April of 1918.

00:08:54.370 --> 00:08:59.490
He served in the states
in field artillery.

00:08:59.490 --> 00:09:02.500
In between guard duty
and 13-mile hikes

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:04.340
and all the other
duties you normally hear

00:09:04.340 --> 00:09:07.790
about in these journals
and diaries and expressions

00:09:07.790 --> 00:09:12.530
of veterans' experience,
he actually talks more

00:09:12.530 --> 00:09:16.200
about the sonnets and
fugues that he was thinking

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:19.150
about from his time
playing the piano.

00:09:19.150 --> 00:09:23.380
And his entire journal isn't
full of the daily doldrums

00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:26.650
of what it was like to be
a soldier, but instead,

00:09:26.650 --> 00:09:30.230
of how Voltaire made
an impression on him.

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:33.120
Of how Tolstoy made
an impression on him.

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:34.780
I love this page in particular.

00:09:34.780 --> 00:09:37.310
Down at the bottom
you can perhaps see

00:09:37.310 --> 00:09:41.740
in his beautifully
expressive script,

00:09:41.740 --> 00:09:44.100
one is made to kiss their books,

00:09:44.100 --> 00:09:49.030
expressing such truth
and sincere thought.

00:09:49.030 --> 00:09:54.920
So you can see from this how
much even in the midst of duty,

00:09:54.920 --> 00:09:57.930
the need to express
and create and interact

00:09:57.930 --> 00:10:02.100
with these items can be
so important to veterans.

00:10:02.100 --> 00:10:04.700
One other collection I want
to draw your attention to is

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:09.830
that of Rona Marie Knox Prescott
who served during Vietnam

00:10:09.830 --> 00:10:13.280
as a nurse in country,
and unfortunately,

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:14.950
lost a dear friend of hers

00:10:14.950 --> 00:10:18.660
through really difficult
circumstances.

00:10:18.660 --> 00:10:22.070
But when she came back,
she found solace in poetry.

00:10:22.070 --> 00:10:24.010
And her poems brought
her great comfort,

00:10:24.010 --> 00:10:26.210
and she left them
at the Vietnam Wall.

00:10:26.210 --> 00:10:28.370
Because she left them
at the Vietnam Wall,

00:10:28.370 --> 00:10:32.470
the family of her friend, who
passed away, was able to connect

00:10:32.470 --> 00:10:34.910
with her, and they found
solace in her poems.

00:10:34.910 --> 00:10:39.320
So I just set these sort of,
to beg a terrible analogy,

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:43.540
touch stones to our
conversation here this morning.

